{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"40f77c15-a518-45f0-9152-1e2115b2fab0","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** on `MauiAppBuilder` to hook platform callbacks without writing platform-specific code:\n\n```csharp\n// In MauiProgram.cs\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` (and the platform-specific namespace, e.g., `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` covers both).\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives so each platform compiles only its own handlers.\n- Other events are available too (`OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnCreate`, etc.) — the builder exposes the full native lifecycle surface.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"465f029e-2b64-49f5-b96c-936543a2ed0a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":354},"id":"0fcbc061-fadf-4b73-b6f4-5d427dcd0c11","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:47:59.998Z","parentId":"a8ba73e5-45d3-42cb-97bd-88bcf11e9fd0"}
